A hitting set is a set of squares such that every possible domino covers at least one square in the set. 1. **Understanding the Problem**: - The grid has 9 squares and 12 possible domino positions (6 horizontal and 6 vertical). - The goal is to find the smallest set of squares (hitting set) that intersects all 12 domino positions. 2. **Graph Representation**: - The problem can be modeled as a graph where each domino is an edge, and each square is a vertex. - The hitting set corresponds to a set of vertices that intersects all edges in the graph. 3. **Independent Set and Hitting Set**: - An independent set in the domino graph is a set of squares where no two are part of the same domino. - The maximum independent set in the domino graph is the largest set of squares with no two adjacent via a domino. 4. **Checkerboard Coloring**: - Using a checkerboard coloring, the grid has 5 squares of one color (e.g., black) and 4 of the other (e.g., white). - Selecting all squares of one color (e.g., black) forms an independent set of size 5, as no two black squares are adjacent. 5. **Hitting Set Calculation**: - The maximum independent set size is 5, so the minimal hitting set size is \(9 - 5 = 4\). 6. **Verification**: - A hitting set of size 4 (e.g., squares 1, 3, 5, 7) is verified to cover all possible domino positions. - Each domino must cover at least one square in the hitting set, ensuring all possible positions are checked. Thus, the minimum number of turns required to guarantee finding at least one covered square is \(\boxed{4}\).
